Detect labels in old ptwiki templates

Before "Template:Marca de projeto" was created, there were separate
templates for each wikiproject, such as "Template:Asteróide/Marca" and
[many
others](https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikip%C3%A9dia:Projetos/Padroniza%C3%A7%C3%A3o/Marcas?oldid=57257364#Marcas_n%C3%A3o-padronizadas)

Not detecting these could make [migration
edits](https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discuss%C3%A3o:Ciclismo_nos_Jogos_Pan-Americanos_de_2007_-_Cross-country_masculino?diff=39571846)
to be treated as if they were the first having a given label.

Add is_scholarlyarticle feature

Scholarly articles have a different structure and often don't have many
labels other than the one in the original language. This impacts them to
a degree larger than what would be appropriate.

Note that this effect likely cannot seen in the current training data
was collected during a time when there were no scholarly articles and
thus contains none.

Reduce the size of wikidata model and simplify its logic

For finding out what's the "Wikimedia reference" (="Imported from
English Wikipedia" for example), this model maintains the whole list of
Wikimedia projects. This is suboptimal for several reasons:
 - The list needs maintaining, there will be new wikis added
 - It'll be slow to check all values against this list
 - It increases the memory footprint of the model (after this change the
   model binary file is 200KB smaller).

You can simply use property P143 instead of the value:
https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Property:P143
Its English label is "imported from Wikimedia project"

I haven't retrained the model yet but I will do it on stat machines
soon.

Split important languages to have their own feature

Currently, if an item has 4 out of 10 important languages as label,
they'll get a feature like "4" which reduces the good predictors like
the difference between English and Chinese. With this change they get a
bigger set of features in a one-hot encoding way. For example
[0, 0, 1, 0, 1, 0, 1, 0, ...]

This increases number of correct predictions on the labelled dataset
from 4175 to 4198 (out of 4951).

Remove impactless property suggester feature

It turned out, that this feature has no significant effect on the
scoring of an item revision. And what slight effect it has seemed to be
minimally negative.

In addition, it comes with significant drawbacks as it requires live
requests to the wikidata API during training and scoring via the API.
Those requests are too numerous while processing dumps, so they were
always skipped there. This meant that revisions could theoretically have
had a different score when scored via the API or based on dumps, which
is also undesirable.
